docs.abstract: Bernie Sanders is increasingly seen as the candidate on the rise. But the Iowa contest is unusually jumbled, and several candidates have realistic hopes for a sudden burst of momentum.
docs.snippet: Bernie Sanders is increasingly seen as the candidate on the rise. But the Iowa contest is unusually jumbled, and several candidates have realistic hopes for a sudden burst of momentum.
docs.lead_paragraph: DES MOINES — The Democratic presidential candidates pleaded with voters in Iowa for their last-minute consideration on Sunday, competing with the Super Bowl for caucusgoers’ attention and straining against an atmosphere of unusual uncertainty and indecision among Democrats ahead of the first-in-the-nation nominating contest.

headline.main: Democrats Make Final Appeals in a Cloudy 2020 Iowa Caucus Race
headline.print_headline: Democratic Hopefuls Make Final Appeals in a Blurred Caucus Race

docs.abstract: As Michael Bloomberg prepares a presidential run, his history of crude remarks is likely to draw scrutiny. His team said some were “disrespectful.”
docs.snippet: As Michael Bloomberg prepares a presidential run, his history of crude remarks is likely to draw scrutiny. His team said some were “disrespectful.”
docs.lead_paragraph: It was a cheeky birthday gift for a hard-charging boss, a 32-page book of one-liners compiled by colleagues at his company. “The Portable Bloomberg: The Wit and Wisdom of Michael Bloomberg,” presented in 1990 to the future mayor of New York City, even featured drawings of its namesake in gladiatorial garb.

headline.main: Michael Bloomberg’s History of Demeaning Comments About Women
headline.print_headline: Bloomberg’s Team Says His Crude Comments About Women Were ‘Wrong’

docs.lead_paragraph: In a moment that briefly froze the debate stage in Charleston, S.C., on Tuesday, Senator Elizabeth Warren explained why she thought Michael R. Bloomberg was the “riskiest” candidate for the Democratic Party to nominate, with a pointed recitation of his history of crude and sexist comments.

headline.main: Elizabeth Warren Challenges Michael Bloomberg on ‘Kill It’ Abortion Comment

docs.lead_paragraph: Michael R. Bloomberg bobbed behind his lectern, as if the motion might deliver him somewhere more comfortable. He blinked, then blinked some more. docs.lead_paragraph: LAS VEGAS — As six leading presidential candidates brawled onstage in a debate Wednesday night on the Las Vegas Strip, a handful of Nevadans supporting a man who didn’t make the cut were around seven miles away, puzzling over their evening plans.

headline.main: Where’s Tom Steyer? A Few People in Las Vegas Were Wondering
headline.print_headline: Steyer Missed Debate Cut, And Nevadans Missed Him

docs.abstract: Michael R. Bloomberg, who was challenged at this week’s Democratic debate over the agreements, said the women had made complaints “about comments they said I had made.” His rivals said it wasn’t enough.
docs.snippet: Michael R. Bloomberg, who was challenged at this week’s Democratic debate over the agreements, said the women had made complaints “about comments they said I had made.” His rivals said it wasn’t enough.
docs.lead_paragraph: LAS VEGAS — Michael R. Bloomberg said Friday that he was willing to release three women from nondisclosure agreements with his company so they could discuss their complaints about him publicly, reversing himself from his position at this week’s Democratic presidential debate when he came under fire from his rivals for resisting such a move.

headline.main: Bloomberg, in Reversal, Says He’ll Release 3 Women From Nondisclosure Agreements
headline.print_headline: Bloomberg Will Release 3 Women From Secrecy
